{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567644","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567644"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:05:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:05:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19184"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19184","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19184"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.23,0.02,0.7,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11918"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81869"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11918","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11918"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19184"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67146"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"2624"},{"type":"tags","id":"3763"},{"type":"tags","id":"6466"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27928"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81869","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81869"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man is admitted to hospital following a high-speed motor vehicle accident. He has sustained blunt abdominal trauma resulting in a splenic rupture requiring emergency splenectomy. His blood type is O positive. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Following surgery, his haemoglobin is 70 g/L (120-160).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETen minutes after commencing a packed red blood cell transfusion, he develops rigors and his temperature rises from 36.8\u00b0C to 38.5\u00b0C. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, and SpO2 98% on room air. He has no rash, chest pain, or difficulty breathing.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of his symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anaphylactic reaction","Acute haemolytic transfusion reaction","Transfusion-related acute lung injury","Febrile non-haemolytic transfusion reaction","Bacterial contamination"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with fever and rigors shortly after starting a blood transfusion. The clinical picture is most consistent with a febrile non-haemolytic transfusion reaction (FNHTR), which is the most common type of transfusion reaction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFebrile non-haemolytic transfusion reaction\u003C/strong\u003E presents with fever (defined as \u22651\u00b0C rise from baseline) and/or rigors within 1-2 hours of starting transfusion. It is caused by cytokines released from white blood cells in stored blood products or by recipient antibodies against donor white blood cells. The reaction is generally self-limiting and responds well to antipyretics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute haemolytic transfusion reaction\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with fever, but also includes other symptoms such as chest pain, back pain, hypotension, and dark urine. These symptoms are not present in this case, and the patient\u0027s blood type was correctly matched.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBacterial contamination\u003C/strong\u003E of blood products can cause rapid onset of fever with hypotension and shock. While this can occur within minutes of starting transfusion, the stability of this patient\u0027s vital signs (apart from fever) makes this less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransfusion-related acute lung injury\u003C/strong\u003E (TRALI) presents with acute respiratory distress and hypoxemia within 6 hours of transfusion. The absence of respiratory symptoms makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnaphylactic reaction\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with urticaria, bronchospasm, hypotension, and respiratory distress. The absence of these symptoms and the presence of isolated fever makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement involves stopping the transfusion, checking vital signs and the blood product details, and administering antipyretics. The transfusion can usually be resumed at a slower rate if symptoms improve and no other cause is identified.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Febrile non-haemolytic transfusion reactions are the most common type of transfusion reaction, typically occurring within 15 minutes to 1 hour of starting the transfusion.","Cytokines released from white blood cells in stored blood products are the primary cause of febrile non-haemolytic transfusion reactions.","While concerning, febrile non-haemolytic transfusion reactions are generally self-limiting and less severe than other transfusion reactions."],"references":["Wang H, Ren D, Sun H, Liu J. Research progress on febrile non-hemolytic transfusion reaction: a narrative review. Annals of Translational Medicine [Internet]. 2022 Dec 1;10(24):1401\u20131. Available from: https://atm.amegroups.com/article/view/106034/html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67146"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19184"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67146","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67146"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-27T10:02:22+10:30",